00:41:27,067 --> 00:41:29,535
Can I have another, please?

518
00:41:29,570 --> 00:41:32,573
To answer your question,
I’m following
breakfast at tiffany's

519
00:41:33,073 --> 00:41:35,040
by blazing a different path.

520
00:41:35,075 --> 00:41:38,579
By inventing an entirely
new kind of writing.

521
00:41:39,079 --> 00:41:40,581
The nonfiction novel.

522
00:41:41,081 --> 00:41:42,833
You have a subject?
Yes.

523
00:41:42,868 --> 00:41:44,550
On the night of November 14,

524
00:41:44,585 --> 00:41:47,087
2 men broke into
a quiet farmhouse in Kansas

525
00:41:47,588 --> 00:41:49,840
and murdered an entire family.

526
00:41:49,875 --> 00:41:52,057
Now, why did they do that?

527
00:41:52,092 --> 00:41:54,595
2 worlds exist
in this country.

528
00:41:55,095 --> 00:41:59,099
The quiet, conservative life,
and the life of those 2 men.

529
00:41:59,134 --> 00:42:02,102
The underbelly.
The criminally violent.

530
00:42:02,603 --> 00:42:05,606
And those worlds converged
that bloody night.

531
00:42:06,106 --> 00:42:07,573
Now, I spent the past 3 months

532
00:42:07,608 --> 00:42:10,611
interviewing
everyone in Kansas
touched by that violence.

533
00:42:11,111 --> 00:42:13,113
Now I spent hours
talking to the killers

534
00:42:13,148 --> 00:42:15,080
and I’ll spend more.

535
00:42:15,115 --> 00:42:18,584
'Cause researching this work
has changed my life.

536
00:42:18,619 --> 00:42:22,122
You know,
it's altered my point of view
about almost everything.

537
00:42:23,123 --> 00:42:24,590
Yeah.

538
00:42:24,625 --> 00:42:28,128
And I think those who read it
will be similarly affected.

539
00:42:48,148 --> 00:42:50,115
So you find them
a new lawyer.

540
00:42:50,150 --> 00:42:54,620
Well, they're facing
execution in 6 weeks.

541
00:42:54,655 --> 00:42:58,659
You know, they need
someone to argue
whether or not that's right.

542
00:43:03,163 --> 00:43:04,129
Ok.

543
00:43:04,164 --> 00:43:06,667
And I’d also like to
see them alive.

544
00:43:07,668 --> 00:43:09,635
Weli...
yeah.

545
00:43:09,670 --> 00:43:12,172
Yeah, I need to
hear their stories.

546
00:43:14,174 --> 00:43:17,177
Well, just be careful
what you do to
get what you want.

547
00:43:17,212 --> 00:43:18,644
I...

548
00:43:18,679 --> 00:43:21,647
I’m finding them a lawyer.

549
00:43:21,682 --> 00:43:23,183
Truman, you're
finding yourself a lawyer.

550
00:43:23,218 --> 00:43:25,185
No, I’m finding them
a lawyer.

551
00:43:27,688 --> 00:43:29,189
There's a difference.

552
00:43:54,915 --> 00:43:56,717
The Warden will see you now.

553
00:44:00,721 --> 00:44:02,723
Well, we do all right
by our boys.
Hmm.

554
00:44:03,223 --> 00:44:05,691
Showers once a week.
Feed them good.

555
00:44:05,726 --> 00:44:09,229
We'll be feeding Perry Smith
in the infirmary soon
if he don't eat.

556
00:44:09,730 --> 00:44:11,481
Try and get the food in
through his arm.

557
00:44:11,516 --> 00:44:13,233
I'm sorry,
what are you talking about?

558
00:44:13,268 --> 00:44:15,753
Well,
he hasn't eaten in a month.

559
00:44:15,788 --> 00:44:18,238
It ain't his right
to kill himself.

560
00:44:18,273 --> 00:44:20,007
It's the right of the people.

561
00:44:20,042 --> 00:44:21,707
The people of this state.

562
00:44:21,742 --> 00:44:23,744
And that's who I work for,
the people.

563
00:44:24,745 --> 00:44:25,746
No one told me.

564
00:44:26,246 --> 00:44:27,247
Yeah, he won't eat.

565
00:44:29,750 --> 00:44:30,751
Uh-huh.

566
00:44:31,752 --> 00:44:33,003
When can I see him?

567
00:44:33,038 --> 00:44:34,254
Well, let me see.

568
00:44:37,758 --> 00:44:40,761
How about you coming 3:00,
Thursday afternoon?

569
00:44:40,796 --> 00:44:41,762
No.

570
00:44:42,262 --> 00:44:43,729
Um...

571
00:44:43,764 --> 00:44:45,265
that's no good.

572
00:44:45,300 --> 00:44:46,732
I...

573
00:44:46,767 --> 00:44:49,234
I need to see them now.

574
00:44:49,269 --> 00:44:53,238
Then... then whenever I want,
for as long as I want.

575
00:44:53,273 --> 00:44:57,277
Well, that's just not
how we do things
around here, Mr. Capote.

576
00:44:59,279 --> 00:45:01,747
Yeah, I understand
what a burden

577
00:45:01,782 --> 00:45:05,285
unlimited visitation might be
on this institution

578
00:45:05,786 --> 00:45:08,789
and on the people
who pay for it.

579
00:45:08,824 --> 00:45:10,756
And I want to be clear

580
00:45:10,791 --> 00:45:13,794
that I don't expect
the citizens
of Leavenworth county

581
00:45:14,294 --> 00:45:16,296
to have to
shoulder that burden.

582
00:45:22,803 --> 00:45:25,305
This is to be dispensed
as you see fit.

583
00:45:38,819 --> 00:45:41,822
You know, I didn't know
where to count your boy
at first,

584
00:45:41,857 --> 00:45:43,824
him being half-Indian.

585
00:45:44,324 --> 00:45:45,791
But I did him a favor.

586
00:45:45,826 --> 00:45:47,327
I counted him as a white man.

587
00:45:49,329 --> 00:45:52,332
Uh-huh. You're a kind
and generous man.

588
00:45:52,367 --> 00:45:53,834
Spread your feet.

589
00:46:02,342 --> 00:46:03,844
This way.

590
00:46:16,356 --> 00:46:17,357
Hey, hey.

591
00:46:17,392 --> 00:46:18,358
Yeah, hello.

592
00:46:19,860 --> 00:46:22,362
Hey,
thanks a lot for your help
with the lawyer.

593
00:46:22,397 --> 00:46:23,864
Oh, that's fine.

594
00:46:26,366 --> 00:46:29,870
Wow, you must be
really desperate for a story
to come all the way out here.

595
00:46:33,874 --> 00:46:36,376
You want to go
see Perry, go ahead.

596
00:46:36,877 --> 00:46:38,343
Thank you.

597
00:46:38,378 --> 00:46:40,212
You want my advice,
though, Mr. Capote,

598
00:46:40,247 --> 00:46:43,250
he's just trying to prove
the insanity defense.

599
00:47:27,127 --> 00:47:28,128
It's ok.

600
00:47:43,644 --> 00:47:44,645
It's ok.

601
00:47:46,146 --> 00:47:49,650
It's Truman.
It's your friend.

602
00:47:54,154 --> 00:47:55,155
It's ok.

603
00:49:38,892 --> 00:49:41,144
This is before she had us.

604
00:49:41,179 --> 00:49:43,397
Before she started drinking.

605
00:49:44,898 --> 00:49:47,401
Who took care of you
as a child?

606
00:49:49,403 --> 00:49:50,404
Orphanage.

607
00:49:51,905 --> 00:49:53,407
Me and Linda.

608
00:49:53,907 --> 00:49:55,409
And that's your sister?

609
00:50:05,919 --> 00:50:09,923
You know,
we're not so different
as you might think.

610
00:50:09,958 --> 00:50:13,927
Yeah, I was abandoned
repeatedly as a child.

611
00:50:19,933 --> 00:50:24,187
My mama would drag me along
to some new town,

612
00:50:24,222 --> 00:50:28,407
so she could take up
with another man she'd met.

613
00:50:28,442 --> 00:50:32,446
Night after night,
she'd lock me
in the hotel room alone.

614
00:50:33,447 --> 00:50:35,949
Mama would turn the latch
and tell the staff

615
00:50:35,984 --> 00:50:37,951
not to let me out
no matter what.

616
00:50:41,955 --> 00:50:43,457
And I was terrified.

617
00:50:46,960 --> 00:50:49,963
And I’d scream my head off...

618
00:50:53,467 --> 00:50:56,435
until finally I’d collapse

619
00:50:56,470 --> 00:51:00,974
on the carpet
next to the door
and I’d fall asleep.

620
00:51:03,977 --> 00:51:06,480
Then after years of this,

621
00:51:06,515 --> 00:51:08,447
she just left me

622
00:51:08,482 --> 00:51:11,985
with relatives in Alabama.

623
00:51:14,988 --> 00:51:16,490
Who raised you up?

624
00:51:17,991 --> 00:51:19,493
My aunts.

625
00:51:22,996 --> 00:51:24,963
And that's where I met Nelle.

626
00:51:24,998 --> 00:51:28,001
And she lived...
she lived next door.

627
00:51:35,008 --> 00:51:37,010
Your mother was Indian?

628
00:51:37,045 --> 00:51:39,478
Cherokee.

629
00:51:39,513 --> 00:51:42,516
So drinking was not
a good thing for her.

630
00:51:44,017 --> 00:51:45,519
No tolerance for it.

631
00:51:57,531 --> 00:52:00,033
We're on, uh, suicide watch.

632
00:52:02,035 --> 00:52:04,037
That's why they leave
the lights on at night.

633
00:52:04,538 --> 00:52:06,540
I hope
we're past that now.

634
00:52:06,575 --> 00:52:07,541
I do.

635
00:52:20,053 --> 00:52:21,555
Be careful of Ricardo.

636
00:52:23,056 --> 00:52:26,059
I think he wants you
all to himself.

637
00:52:26,094 --> 00:52:27,526
All right.

638
00:52:27,561 --> 00:52:29,563
But he's
naturally mendacious.

639
00:52:30,564 --> 00:52:32,566
Not to be trusted.

640
00:52:33,066 --> 00:52:36,069
If he had $100,
he'd steal a stick
of chewing gum.

641
00:52:46,580 --> 00:52:49,583
Perry,
I want to take
your notebooks with me.

642
00:52:51,585 --> 00:52:53,587
I want to read them.

643
00:52:55,589 --> 00:52:58,091
If I leave here
without understanding you,

644
00:52:59,593 --> 00:53:02,596
the world will see you
as a monster

645
00:53:03,096 --> 00:53:04,097
always.

646
00:53:07,100 --> 00:53:09,102
I don't want that.

647
00:53:33,627 --> 00:53:35,128
'Cause he trusts me.

648
00:53:35,629 --> 00:53:37,464
I mean,
that's why he gave it to me.

649
00:53:37,964 --> 00:53:41,968
And he-he's given me
absolutely everything.

650
00:53:42,003 --> 00:53:45,972
And he wants so badly
to be taken seriously

651
00:53:46,007 --> 00:53:48,475
to be held in some esteem.

652
00:53:48,510 --> 00:53:49,476
Do you?

653
00:53:49,511 --> 00:53:50,942
Do I what?

654
00:53:50,977 --> 00:53:53,480
Do you hold him
in esteem, Truman?

655
00:53:55,982 --> 00:53:56,983
Well,

656
00:53:59,486 --> 00:54:00,987
he's a gold mine.

657
00:54:02,989 --> 00:54:05,492
And he's told me
his entire life.

658
00:54:05,992 --> 00:54:06,993
His, uh,

659
00:54:07,494 --> 00:54:08,960
his dead mother.

660
00:54:08,995 --> 00:54:11,998
Uh, he had a brother
and a sister kill themselves.

661
00:54:12,499 --> 00:54:13,500
Awful.

662
00:54:15,001 --> 00:54:17,003
Did you tell him
your mama did the same thing?

663
00:54:17,038 --> 00:54:18,505
See, I can't tell him
everything.

664
00:54:19,005 --> 00:54:21,508
We've been
talking our heads off
for the past month.

665
00:54:21,543 --> 00:54:23,510
And sometimes when I...

666
00:54:26,012 --> 00:54:29,516
when I think how good
my book can be,
I can hardly breathe.

667
00:54:35,522 --> 00:54:38,525
Anyway, th-this is...
this is what I wanted
to read to you.

668
00:54:38,560 --> 00:54:39,526
Uh,

669
00:54:40,026 --> 00:54:41,778
"if called upon
to make a speech..."

670
00:54:41,813 --> 00:54:43,530
"if called upon
to make a speech"?

671
00:54:44,030 --> 00:54:47,033
I mean, this is exactly
what I’m talking about.

672
00:54:47,534 --> 00:54:51,788
A speech, just in case
he's ever recognized
for an achievement.

673
00:54:51,823 --> 00:54:56,042
"I can't remember
what I was going to say
for the life of me.

674
00:54:56,077 --> 00:54:58,044
"I don't think ever
before have so many people

675
00:54:58,545 --> 00:55:00,011
"been so directly responsible

676
00:55:00,046 --> 00:55:02,514
"for my being
so very, very glad.

677
00:55:02,549 --> 00:55:05,051
"It's a wonderful moment
and a rare one.

678
00:55:06,052 --> 00:55:08,019
Thank you!"

679
00:55:08,054 --> 00:55:10,557
There's... there's an
exclamation point at
the end of that "thank you"

680
00:55:11,057 --> 00:55:12,559
in case you didn't catch it.

681
00:55:16,062 --> 00:55:17,564
Where'd you go?

682
00:55:20,066 --> 00:55:23,069
I guess it
stopped being funny.

683
00:55:23,104 --> 00:55:25,071
I... I never said it was.

684
00:55:26,573 --> 00:55:28,074
But, wait,
listen to this.

685
00:55:29,861 --> 00:55:31,042
I was 14.

686
00:55:31,077 --> 00:55:34,581
One day I said to him,
"mom's dead."
I could see it.

687
00:55:34,616 --> 00:55:36,350
A week later we got the news.

688
00:55:36,385 --> 00:55:37,735
She finally drunk
herself...

689
00:55:37,770 --> 00:55:39,085
...found her shivering...

690
00:55:39,586 --> 00:55:41,588
she hit me so many times
with that flashlight,

691
00:55:41,623 --> 00:55:43,089
she broke it.

692
00:55:43,590 --> 00:55:44,591
That night, I...
I dreamed about
that big yellow bird.

693
00:55:45,091 --> 00:55:46,593
Clawed that nun's eyes,
bright like the sun.

694
00:55:46,628 --> 00:55:48,560
Lifted me to the sky.

695
00:55:48,595 --> 00:55:51,598
Sometimes you see a thing
how it really is.

696
00:55:58,104 --> 00:56:01,107
Well, you're nothing
if not hardworking.

697
00:56:01,142 --> 00:56:03,109
Hey, you look good.
Healthy again.

698
00:56:07,113 --> 00:56:10,116
You know, I’ve decided
on a title for my book.

699
00:56:11,618 --> 00:56:13,303
I think you'll like it.

700
00:56:13,338 --> 00:56:14,988
It's very masculine.

701
00:56:15,989 --> 00:56:17,490
In cold blood.

702
00:56:18,491 --> 00:56:19,993
Isn't that good?

703
00:56:21,461 --> 00:56:23,463
And that refers to the crime

704
00:56:23,963 --> 00:56:26,966
or the fact that
you're still talking
to the criminals?

705
00:56:29,469 --> 00:56:32,472
Oh, the former,
among other things.

706
00:56:33,973 --> 00:56:34,974
I see.

707
00:56:40,980 --> 00:56:42,447
I wanted to ask

708
00:56:42,482 --> 00:56:46,486
if you'd let me look
at your investigation notes.

709
00:56:46,521 --> 00:56:49,454
That lawyer you helped find
for your friends

710
00:56:49,489 --> 00:56:52,492
got them a hearing at
the Kansas supreme court...

711
00:56:52,527 --> 00:56:53,958
yeah, I heard this morning.

712
00:56:53,993 --> 00:56:56,496
...on the issue
of inadequate counsel.

713
00:57:02,502 --> 00:57:04,969
Alvin,

714
00:57:05,004 --> 00:57:09,008
I mean,
do you not want me
to look at your notes?

715
00:57:09,043 --> 00:57:11,010
You are permitted to say no.

716
00:57:19,018 --> 00:57:20,437
I'll tell you what.

717
00:57:21,438 --> 00:57:23,440
If those boys get off,

718
00:57:24,441 --> 00:57:26,943
I’m coming to Brooklyn
to hunt you down.

719
00:57:29,446 --> 00:57:31,913
I have to be in court
at 9:00,

720
00:57:31,948 --> 00:57:35,952
but you call Roy Church
and he'll show you
what you want to see.

721
00:57:39,956 --> 00:57:41,458
Thank you.

722
00:57:42,459 --> 00:57:44,843
It's as much for me
as for anyone.

723
00:57:44,878 --> 00:57:48,631
I couldn't bear the thought
of losing you so soon.

724
00:57:48,666 --> 00:57:52,350
We're gonna be able
to use your book
for our case.

725
00:57:52,385 --> 00:57:55,388
You... you'll write
we never got to raise
an insanity plea.

726
00:57:57,390 --> 00:57:59,893
You wrote how terrible
the lawyers was.

727
00:58:02,896 --> 00:58:05,398
I... I haven't written
a word yet.

728
00:58:14,908 --> 00:58:16,409
What have you been doing?

729
00:58:17,911 --> 00:58:20,413
Research. Talking to you.

730
00:58:24,918 --> 00:58:26,885
All right.

731
00:58:26,920 --> 00:58:27,886
I... I had hoped...

732
00:58:27,921 --> 00:58:29,422
wh-what are you calling it?

733
00:58:31,925 --> 00:58:33,426
The book?

734
00:58:35,929 --> 00:58:37,430
I have no idea.

735
00:58:41,434 --> 00:58:43,902
Perry,

736
00:58:43,937 --> 00:58:46,404
if I’m going to
write about you,

737
00:58:46,439 --> 00:58:50,944
if I’m going to determine
how to write about you,

738
00:58:51,945 --> 00:58:53,947
we need to talk about,

739
00:58:54,948 --> 00:58:56,950
you know, why you're here.

740
00:58:58,952 --> 00:58:59,953
And,

741
00:59:01,454 --> 00:59:02,956
you know, the murders,

742
00:59:02,991 --> 00:59:05,423
and that night

743
00:59:05,458 --> 00:59:06,960
at the clutter house.

744
00:59:16,469 --> 00:59:18,972
Do you worry
what I’ll think?

745
00:59:19,007 --> 00:59:20,473
Is that it?

746
00:59:23,476 --> 00:59:25,979
Dick says you know
Elizabeth Taylor.

747
00:59:28,481 --> 00:59:29,983
I know a lot of people.

748
00:59:37,490 --> 00:59:41,494
Perry, I have invitations
to be in morocco, Greece,

749
00:59:43,496 --> 00:59:45,999
and I prefer to be here

750
00:59:46,034 --> 00:59:47,500
with you.

751
00:59:55,008 --> 00:59:58,261
Jack, be patient with me.

752
00:59:58,296 --> 01:00:01,479
I'm just missing
this one piece.

753
01:00:01,514 --> 01:00:03,481
Well, how long
is that gonna take?

754
01:00:03,516 --> 01:00:06,019
Why don't you just
try leaving him alone
for a while?

755
01:00:06,054 --> 01:00:07,986
Come to Spain.

756
01:00:08,021 --> 01:00:10,023
You can always
visit him later.

757
01:00:10,058 --> 01:00:11,990
I don't know.

758
01:00:12,025 --> 01:00:15,028
Well, I’m off.
I'm just... I’ve got
my own writing to do.

759
01:00:15,063 --> 01:00:18,298
Well, do it in Brooklyn.
Wait for me.

760
01:00:18,333 --> 01:00:21,499
There's too many
people around. I've...

761
01:00:21,534 --> 01:00:23,536
I’ll leave the address
on the kitchen table.

762
01:00:26,039 --> 01:00:29,042
Well,
think about what I said,
and join me when you can.

763
01:00:30,543 --> 01:00:32,010
I will.

764
01:00:32,045 --> 01:00:33,046
I will.
Ok?

765
01:00:33,546 --> 01:00:34,547
Bye.

766
01:00:58,571 --> 01:00:59,572
Hi.

767
01:01:22,045 --> 01:01:23,546
Truman.

768
01:01:24,047 --> 01:01:26,549
We never intended
on killing that family.

769
01:01:27,550 --> 01:01:28,551
Capote,

770
01:01:29,052 --> 01:01:31,054
will you get that straight
in your book, please?

771
01:01:31,089 --> 01:01:33,056
No premeditation.

772
01:01:33,556 --> 01:01:35,308
What are you doing?

773
01:01:35,343 --> 01:01:37,060
I have to fly back east.

